<section xml:id="sec-cylindrical-spherical">
  <title>Cylindrical and spherical coordinates</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Introduce cylindrical and spherical coordinate systems and relate them to Cartesian coordinates.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute the associated Jacobians that describe how volume elements transform.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Rewrite triple integrals in these coordinates when symmetry simplifies computation.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        3D Jacobians are set up the same way, but might need to show how determinant works (expansion by minors or maybe Rule of Sarrus would be enough)
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Cylindrical coordinates:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x \amp = r\cos\theta</mrow>
        <mrow>y \amp = r\sin\theta</mrow>
        <mrow>z \amp = z</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Jacobian: <m>\DS\abs{\pdv{(x,y,z)}{(r,\theta,z)}}=r</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Spherical coordinates:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x \amp = \rho\sin\phi\cos\theta</mrow>
        <mrow>y \amp = \rho\sin\phi\sin\theta</mrow>
        <mrow>z \amp = \rho\cos\phi</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Jacobian: <m>\DS\abs{\pdv{(x,y,z)}{(\rho,\theta,\phi)}}=\rho^{2}\sin\phi</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        This is assuming <m>\rho</m> is spherical radius, <m>\theta</m> is longitude (azimuthal angle), <m>\phi</m> is co-latitude (polar angle).
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Show how to use them to convert triple integrals, applied problems (most likely center of mass, moment of inertia)
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
